claim.claim-text:
1. A method for coupling optical wavelength division multiplexed (OWDM) networks having one or more OWDM channels, the method comprising the steps of: 
receiving the one or more OWDM channels from a first OWDM network, each OWDM channel having a different OWDM wavelength; 
converting each one of the one or more OWDM channels to a wireless wavelength division multiplexing (WWDM) channel to produce one or more WWDM channels at a plurality of WWDM wavelengths, each WWDM wavelength for each WWDM channel being different from the WWDM wavelength for each other WWDM channel, and each WWDM wavelength corresponding to an OWDM wavelength; 
radiating the one or more WWDM channels; 
receiving the one or more WWDM channels; 
converting each received WWDM channel from the WWDM wavelength for the received WWDM channel to the corresponding OWDM wavelength for the received WWDM channel to produce one or more received OWDM channels; and 
coupling the one or more received OWDM channels into a second OWDM network.

8. The method as claimed in claim 7, further comprising the steps of: 
transmitting one or more communication signals from one or more of the radio frequency users, each communication signal being at one of the WWDM wavelengths of the plurality of WWDM wavelengths; 
receiving the one or more communication signals; 
converting each one of the one or more communication signals at the WWDM wavelengths to a received communication signal at the OWDM wavelength assigned to the WWDM wavelength; and 
coupling the received communication signal to the first OWDM network or to the second OWDM network.

9. The method as claimed in claim 2, wherein the step of converting each one of the one or more OWDM channels to a wireless wavelength division multiplexing (WWDM) channel to produce one or more WWDM channels comprises the steps of: 
providing a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequencies; 
demultiplexing each one of the one or more OWDM channels into one or more separate optical signals; 
converting the one or more separate optical signals into one or more baseband electrical signals; 
modulating each one of the one or more baseband electrical signals with a separate intermediate frequency of the plurality of intermediate frequencies to produce one or more modulated intermediate frequency signals; and 
up-converting each one of the one or more modulated intermediate frequency signals to produce the one or more WWDM channels.

10. The method as claimed in claim 2, wherein the step of converting each received WWDM channel from the WWDM wavelength for the received WWDM channel to the corresponding OWDM wavelength comprises the steps of: 
providing a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequencies; 
downconverting each one of the received WWDM channels to produce one or more downconverted signals; 
demodulating each one of the downconverted signals with a separate intermediate frequency of the plurality of intermediate frequencies to produce one or more received baseband signals; 
converting each one of the received baseband signals to a received optical signal, each received optical signal being at the OWDM wavelength of the OWDM channel corresponding to the WWDM channel from which each received optical signal is derived; and 
multiplexing each one of the received optical signals to produce one or more received OWDM channels.

16. The method as claimed in claim 1, wherein the method further comprises the steps of: 
converting voice/data services from one or more wireless users to one or more voice/data WWDM channels at WWDM wavelengths; 
radiating the one or more voice/data WWDM channels from one or more wireless users; 
receiving the one or more voice/data WWDM channels; 
converting each received voice/data WWDM channels from the WWDM wavelength for the voice/data WWDM channel to the corresponding OWDM wavelength for the WWDM wavelength to produce one or more received voice/data OWDM channels; and 
coupling the one or more received voice/data OWDM channels into the first or second OWDM network.

17. The method as claimed in claim 1, wherein one or more of the OWDM channels are allocated for voice/data services and the method further comprises the steps of: 
converting one or more of the OWDM channels allocated for network voice/data services to one or more network voice/data WWDM channels; 
radiating the one or more network voice/data WWDM channels; 
receiving the one or more network voice/data WWDM channels at one or more wireless users; 
extracting the network voice/data services from the one or more network voice/data WWDM channels; 
converting user voice/data services from one or more wireless users to one or more user voice/data WWDM channels at WWDM wavelengths; 
radiating the one or more user voice/data WWDM channels; 
receiving the one or more user voice/data WWDM channels; 
converting each user voice/data WWDM channels from the WWDM wavelength for the user voice/data WWDM channel to the corresponding OWDM wavelength for the WWDM wavelength to produce one or more user voice/data OWDM channels; and 
coupling the one or more user voice/data OWDM channels into the first or second OWDM network.

19. A wireless wavelength division multiplexing (WWDM) system for coupling optical wavelength division multiplexed (OWDM) networks comprising: 
one or more WWDM transmitters receiving one or more optical wavelength division multiplexed (OWDM) channels, each OWDM channel having a different OWDM wavelength, said WWDM transmitter converting the one or more OWDM channels to one or more WWDM channels, each WWDM channel having a different WWDM wavelength; 
one or more radiating apertures coupled to each WWDM transmitter, said radiating apertures radiating the WWDM channels; 
one or more receiving apertures receiving WWDM channels; 
one or more WWDM receivers coupled to the one or more receiving apertures, each WWDM receiver receiving one or more received WWDM channels, and each WWDM receiver converting the one or more received WWDM channels to one or more OWDM channels.

26. The system as claimed in claim 19, wherein at least one WWDM transmitter comprises: 
an OWDM demultiplexer; 
an optical-to-electrical converter coupled to the OWDM demultiplexer and producing one or more baseband electrical signals; 
a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequency signals; 
a bank of modulators, each modulator in the bank of modulators receiving a baseband electrical signal from the optical-to-electrical converter and receiving an intermediate frequency signal from the comb frequency generator and producing a modulated intermediate frequency electrical signal; and 
one or more upconverters receiving the modulated intermediate frequency signals and producing the one or more WWDM channels.

27. The system as claimed in claim 19, wherein at least one WWDM receiver comprises: 
one or more downconverters receiving the one or more received WWDM channels and producing one or more received downconverted signals; 
a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequency signals; 
a bank of demodulators, each demodulator in the bank of demodulators receiving one of the one or more received downconverted signals from the one or more downconverters and receiving an intermediate frequency signal from the comb frequency generator and producing a demodulated baseband electrical signal; 
an electrical-to-optical converter receiving each one of the demodulated baseband electrical signals and producing an optical signal for each demodulated baseband electrical signal at an OWDM wavelength corresponding to the WWDM wavelength for the WWDM channel from which the optical signal is derived; and 
an OWDM multiplexer receiving each optical signal and producing the one or more OWDM channels.

28. The system as claimed in claim 19, wherein at least one WWDM transmitter and at least one WWDM receiver are combined into a WWDM transceiver, the WWDM transceiver comprising: 
an OWDM demultiplexer; 
an optical-to-electrical converter coupled to the OWDM demultiplexer and producing one or more baseband electrical signals; 
a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequency signals; 
a bank of modulators, each modulator in the bank of modulators receiving a baseband electrical signal from the optical-to-electrical converter and receiving an intermediate frequency signal from the comb frequency generator and producing a modulated intermediate frequency electrical signal; 
one or more upconverters receiving the modulated baseband signals and producing the one or more WWDM channels; 
one or more downconverters receiving the one or more received WWDM channels and producing one or received downconverted signals; 
a bank of demodulators, each demodulator in the bank of demodulators receiving one of the one or more received downconverted signals from the one or more downconverters and receiving an intermediate frequency signal from the comb frequency generator and producing a demodulated baseband electrical signal; 
an electrical-to-optical converter receiving each one of the demodulated baseband electrical signals and producing an optical signal for each demodulated baseband electrical signal at an OWDM wavelength corresponding to the WWDM wavelength for the WWDM channel from which the optical signal is derived; and 
an OWDM multiplexer receiving each optical signal and producing the one or more OWDM channels.

37. A method for distributing voice or data services to one or more users at one or more radio frequency bands, the method comprising the steps of: 
receiving the voice or data services in one or more OWDM channels from a network operations center, each OWDM channel having a different OWDM wavelength; 
converting each one of the one or more OWDM channels to a transmitted wireless wavelength division multiplexing (WWDM) channel to produce one or more transmitted WWDM channels at a plurality of WWDM wavelengths, the WWDM wavelengths being at radio frequencies, each WWDM wavelength for each transmitted WWDM channel being different from the WWDM wavelength for each other transmitted WWDM channel, and each WWDM wavelength corresponding to an OWDM wavelength; 
radiating the one or more transmitted WWDM channels; and, 
receiving the transmitted WWDM channels.

39. The method as claimed in claim 37, further comprising the steps of: 
transmitting the voice or data services from one or more users in a user transmitted WWDM channel at a selected WWDM wavelength; 
receiving the user transmitted WWDM channel; 
converting the user transmitted WWDM channel to an OWDM channel at the OWDM wavelength corresponding to the selected WWDM wavelength; and 
coupling the OWDM channel to the network operations center.

42. The system as claimed in claim 40, further comprising: 
one or more users transmitting the voice or data services in one or more user transmitted WWDM channels, each user transmitted WWDM channel at a selected WWDM wavelength; 
one or more receiving apertures receiving the one or more user transmitted WWDM channels; 
one or more WWDM receivers coupled to the one or more receiving apertures, each WWDM receiver receiving the one or more user transmitted WWDM channels, and each WWDM receiver converting the one or more user transmitted WWDM channels to one or more OWDM channels, the one or more OWDM channels being coupled to the network operations center.

49. The method as claimed in claim 44, wherein the step of converting each one of the one or more OWDM channels to a WWDM channel to produce one or more WWDM channels comprises the steps of: 
providing a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequencies; 
demultiplexing each one of the one or more OWDM channels into one or more separate optical signals; 
converting the one or more separate optical signals into one or more baseband electrical signals; 
modulating each one of the one or more baseband electrical signals with a separate intermediate frequency of the plurality of intermediate frequencies to produce one or more modulated intermediate frequency signals; and 
up-converting each one of the one or more intermediate frequency signals to produce the one or more WWDM channels.

52 A wireless wavelength division multiplexing transmitter transmitting one or more optical wavelength division multiplexed (OWDM) channels at wireless wavelengths, said transmitter comprising: 
an optical-to-electrical converter receiving said OWDM channels and producing one or more baseband electrical signals; 
a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequency signals; 
a bank of modulators, each modulator in the bank of modulators receiving a baseband electrical signal from the optical-to-electrical converter and receiving an intermediate frequency signal from the comb frequency generator and producing a modulated intermediate frequency electrical signal; and 
one or more upconverters receiving the modulated baseband signals and producing one or more wireless wavelength division multiplexed channels at wireless wavelengths.

65. The method as claimed in claim 59, wherein the step of converting each one of the received WWDM channels from the WWDM wavelength for that WWDM channel comprises the steps of: 
providing a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequencies; 
downconverting each one of the received WWDM channels to produce one or more downconverted signals; 
demodulating each one of the downconverted signals with a separate intermediate frequency of the plurality of intermediate frequencies to produce one or more received baseband signals; 
converting each one of the received baseband signals to a received optical signal, each received optical signal being at the corresponding OWDM wavelength; and 
multiplexing each one of the received optical signals to produce one or more received OWDM channels.

67. A wireless wavelength division multiplexed (WWDM) receiver converting WWDM channels at different WWDM wavelengths to corresponding optical wavelength division multiplexed (OWDM) channels, said receiver comprising: 
one or more downconverters receiving the one or received WWDM channels and producing one or received baseband signals; 
a comb frequency generator producing a plurality of intermediate frequency signals; 
a bank of demodulators, each demodulator in the bank of demodulators receiving one of the one or more received baseband signals from the one or more downconverters and receiving an intermediate frequency signal from the comb frequency generator and producing a demodulated baseband electrical signal; 
an electrical-to-optical converter receiving each one of the demodulated baseband electrical signals and producing an optical signal for each demodulated baseband electrical signal at an OWDM wavelength corresponding to the WWDM wavelength for the WWDM channel from which the optical signal is derived; and 
an OWDM multiplexer receiving each optical signal and producing the one or more OWDM channels.
